Load Data

data <- read.csv("census_data.csv")
data$income.g50 <- rep(0, nrow(data))
data$income.g50[data$income==" >50K"] <- 1

a.)

The log odds ratio for having a masters degree is 2.91 and for having 1st to 4th grade education is -0.18

The log odds ratio for having a masters degree is 18.3567986 and for having 1st to 4th grade education is 0.8352702

The p-value for Masters degree is < 2e -16 hence it is statistically significant but the p-value for 1st - 4th grade education is 0.78371 hence there is more probability that this is by chance.

0.0227273 is the adjusted alpha level. So we can see that the p-value for Masters is lower than 0.0227273 so it is significant however education 1st -4th is 0.78371 hence it isnt as signficant

b.)

P-values for both age and sex are < 2e-16 therefore they are both statistically significant and are practically significant as age and sex do determine a persons income

3

x <- data$age
plot(x, data$income.g50, col="blue")
fits <- fitted(mod)
points(x, fits, pch=19, cex=0.3)

The predicted outcomes are so variable because although age is on the x-axis the other variables vary and thats why we dont have just one sigmoid line

  1. Plot the ROC and calculate the AUC. Again, does this model out perform the other model?
library(AUC)
y <- factor(data$income.g50)
rr <- roc(fits, y)
plot(rr)

auc(rr)
## [1] 0.8893198

This model does outperform the other model as the auc is 0.889 whereas the earlier model is 0.808
